<p>

<p>
 The parameter <code>configuration.queueMaxMemory</code> (see <a class="el" href="group___i_p_d_r__configuration__values.html">Configuration values for inialization (programmatically/MIB)</a>) controls the size of the internal queue. It can be set to 0 (meaning <em>unlimited</em>). If a limit is set, it should be: <br>
 maximum-records-per-second � * (average-record-length + 16) �worst-case-failover-time.
<p>
(16 is the length of the IPDR record header.)
<p>
When the queue fills up, each <em>new</em> record is thrown away and the <a class="el" href="group___i_p_d_r__event__notification.html#a4a152">IPDR_EVENT_RECORD_LOST</a> event is raised. (The reasons for throwing away the new record and not removing the oldest record are (a) it's much more complicated to program and (b) the oldest record might be partially transmitted and there is no way in general to abort its transfer.
<p>
The queue size affects the configuration of a de-duplicator (see <a class="el" href="group___i_p_d_r__reliability__deduplication.html">De-duplication</a> for more details). <hr><address style="align: right;"><small>Generated on Thu Feb 17 22:31:40 2005 for IPDRAPI by
